post_text: The U.S Census is currently underway. The deadline to respond online, by mail or phone has been extended. The census provides critical data that lawmakers, business owners, teachers, and many others use to provide daily services, products, and support for you and your community. Every year, billions of dollars in federal funding go to hospitals, fire departments, roads, and other resources based on census data. The results of the census also determine the number of seats each state will have in the U.S. House of Representatives, and they are used to draw congressional and state legislative districts. The 2020 Census will mark the 24th time that the country has counted its population since 1790. To fill out the census visit https://my2020census.gov/

post_text: New Caney High School student Carter Holton competed last week at the most unconventional National History Day competition for 2020. The contest, held virtually due to COVID-19, consisted of students from around the United States. Holton placed sixth in the Individual Exhibit category. His topic: Breaking Barriers of the CCC, One Park at a Time. CCC stands for Civilian Conservation Corp, a work relief program created during the Great Depression to assist the unemployed. Congratulations Carter! #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles

New Caney ISD would like to honor Kelly Smoot of Oakley Elementary School who was named NCISD Elementary Teacher of the Year! Smoot, a second-grade teacher, has been with New Caney ISD for five years.

"Ms. Smoot does an amazing job. She creates a cool classroom environment that is fun and engaging for all students while inspiring them to reach their highest potential. She has a great rapport with students, parents, and colleagues, always smiling and bringing joy to others around her."

Erica Gruber
Principal, Oakley Elementary School

New Caney ISD has been a pioneer of the Two-Way Dual Language Program for over a decade. Our Two-Way Dual Language program is an enrichment program in which all the content areas (Math, Science, Reading, and Social Studies) are taught in both English and Spanish. Through this program, students have access to a wide variety of experiences to help them develop the Spanish language in an authentic way!

If you are an interested parent of an incoming Kindergarten student, please click on the link below:

https://forms.gle/NznCcG2Sx8TKyCa1A

The Greater Houston Area Girls Basketball Association named New Caney High School girls basketball coach Tricia Mize as Honorary Coach of the GHAGBA 2020 All-Star Team which was announced Thursday, May 7. The GHAGBA also announced it is establishing a scholarship in Coach Mize’s name to begin next year. Mize, who taught and coached at New Caney High School for six years, passed away in April.

GHAGBA Board Member Jennifer Alexander, girls basketball coach at Cypress Creek High School, said Coach Mize “was a class act in our profession, a resilient fighter, and genuine in every act she committed. The scholarship will reflect those characteristics.”

post_text: New Caney HS students competed this week at the most unconventional Texas History Day competition for 2020. The contest, held virtually due to COVID-19, consisted of over 900 students statewide. Nineteen NCHS students, consisting of 11 juniors and eight freshmen, finished with top awards amongst their peers with Carter Holton winning his Individual Exhibit category and advancing to nationals with his topic Breaking Barriers of the CCC One Park at a Time. He will compete later in May at the national level. NCHS group documentary consisting of juniors Arturo Hernandez, Ismael Rami, Layla Brewer, Cheryl Fonseca and Robert Creamer, also won first place for the Willie Lee Gray African American History Award scholarship award. School and district history was made with these awards and the students are excited NCHS will again be represented at History Fair Nationals! Congratulations! #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles

Nineteen NCHS students, consisting of 11 juniors and eight freshmen, finished with top awards amongst their peers with Carter Holton winning his Individual Exhibit category and advancing to nationals with his topic Breaking Barriers of the CCC One Park at a Time. He will compete later in May at the national level. NCHS group documentary consisting of juniors Arturo Hernandez, Ismael Rami, Layla Brewer, Cheryl Fonseca and Robert Creamer, also won first place for the Willie Lee Gray African American History Award scholarship award. School and district history was made with these awards and the students are excited NCHS will again be represented at History Fair Nationals! Congratulations! #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles

post_text: The New Caney ISD instruction and technology departments are implementing plans to support continued learning. Elementary teachers and secondary homeroom teachers are contacting parents to determine their students’ learning needs. After assessing student needs, teachers will communicate with students and parents regarding next steps for receiving instruction, learning materials, and resources. Teachers will be utilizing Canvas, an online learning management system, to share instructional resources and materials. Secondary students currently utilize Canvas, and elementary teachers are sharing information with parents about accessing Canvas. https://newcaneyisd.instructure.com/login/canvas

Beginning Monday, March 23, New Caney ISD’s curbside meal service will take place from 8:30 a.m. to 11:30 a.m. for both breakfast and lunch. This will be the schedule through Friday, April 17. There is no charge for children 18 and under.
Adult meals are $2.75 for breakfast and $4 for lunch. Locations remain New Caney Elementary School and Sorters Mill Elementary School.

New Caney ISD Provee Servicio de Comida

A partir del lunes, 23 de marzo, el Departamento de Nutrición Infantil de New Caney ISD estará sirviendo desayuno y almuerzo de 8:30 a.m. a 11:30 a.m. hasta el viernes, 17 de abril. No se le cobrará a personas menores de 18 años.

Se le cobrarán $2.75 a los adultos por cada desayuno y $4 por cada almuerzo. Las comidas se servirán en New Caney Elementary School y Sorters Mill Elementary School.

On March 2, 1836, Texas declared its independence from Mexico. It later joined the US in 1845 but remains the only state to have existed as its own country. Texans are known for their Texas pride and knowledge. Take this 10 question quiz on Texas Symbolism to see how well you know our home state. Extra points for detailed responses.
#NCISD
#Texas

shared_text:
VYPE.COM
VYPE FILM: Inside the Kitchen with New Caney's Orian Wormley

VYPE Texas
February 26 at 12:00 AM ·

VYPE FILM

Orian Wormley may be known best for his play on the football field for the New Caney Eagles.

But the junior is more than a star on the gridiron. He is also a rising star in the kitchen with the New Caney High School Culinary Arts program, led by Cherie Henning.

VYPE's Joshua Koch headed into the kitchen with Wormley to have him showcase his culinary skills by making fish tacos with mango salsa and guacamole. New Caney ISD New Caney Football Boosters New Caney High School

The Porter High School Texas Association of Future Educators student group participated in the Teach Tomorrow Summit state competition in McAllen, Texas Feb. 20-22.

Ana Martinez - Interactive Bulletin Board - Elementary
Arissa Alaniz - Interactive Bulletin Board - Middle School
Avorie Smith and Chesney DeVoltz - Interactive Bulletin Board - Secondary

The following students participated in the National events for Educators Rising:

Julie Serrano - Job Interview and Exploring Careers Non Core
Shania Castillo - Public Speaking
Guadalupe Perez Manriquez and Itzayana Gonzalez -Children's Literature Pre-K
Guadalupe Perez Manriquez, Itzayana Gonzalez, and Shania Castillo - Researching Learning Challenges

post_text: New Caney ISD Fine Arts is proud to introduce our TMEA All-State Musicians. Ne’Vaeh Young (Sophomore Choir Student, NCHS) Jesse Galindo (Junior Trumpet Player, PHS) and Graydon Harrison (Junior Bassoonist, PHS). Not pictured is Isaac Bulamu (Junior NCHS Choir Student) who was named first alternate to All-State Tenor Bass Choir. To earn a spot in the All-State Choir or Band is a grand accomplishment. This is the first time in school history that @porterhs_spartans has had two All-Staters in the same year and the first time in 17 years that @newcaneyhs has had an all-state choir member. @newcaneyisd and @newcaneyfinearts couldn’t be more proud of these students' efforts and their teachers’ guidance. Congratulations to all and way to go NCISD Fine Arts! #ncisdfinearts #ncisd #musiceducation #musiceducationmatters #tmeaallstate2020

post_text: Congratulations to Porter HS Band students Jesse Galindo (trumpet) and Graydon Harrison (bassoon) who both are now TMEA All Staters! Jesse and Graydon placed 1st chair on their instruments and will travel to San Antonio to represent Porter, NCISD, Region 33 and Area F at the Texas Music Educators Association convention in San Antonio in February. This is the first time in PHS band program history to ever have two all state band students. #NCISD #PHS_Spartans #TMEA #Band

post_text: NCHS Lady Eagles basketball player Micha Mize was named the AT&T Sportsnet Player of the Week Jan. 8. Mize is a junior and has been averaging 16-plus points a game for the season. She also recently received the Houston Chronicle Player of the Week for her performance in the Dekaney tournament over the Christmas break averaging 20.5 points per game. On Jan. 7, she hit six three-pointers and had 20 points against Grand Oaks. Congratulations Micha! #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles #Basketball #ATTSportsNetSW

post_text: New Caney HS Associate Principal Jonathan Powell volunteered to stay on the roof of the school overnight if the students raised $1,000 to help 40 families and 150 children in the area with food and gift items for Christmas. The students raised more than $2,000 in cash and over $5,000 in gifts and food items. Powell was able to raise some of the money by challenging the students. For every $50 they raised, he would run a mile on the roof. He ran six miles due to the donations from the challenge. Thank you Mr. Powell for helping to raise money for our residents and children. #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles #Christmas #EaglesAngels

post_text: The NCISD 14th Annual Jingle Bell Fun Run/Walk is scheduled for Dec. 14 at Porter High School track from 9 a.m. to 10 a.m. Registration starts at 8:15 a.m. The purpose of this event is to help any NCISD student or staff member that is battling an illness or disease and is in need of medical financial assistance. If you know of a NCISD student or staff member in need, please email Dr. Mary Ford at mlford@newcaneyisd.org. Register today to participate. The cost is $20 pre-registration and $25 on-site registration. Free prizes will be given at the event. #NCISD

post_text: The community is invited to see the NCHS Theater Department production of The Odd Couple by Neil Simon. The play is about two recently divorced men with completely opposite personalities who decide to live together. One is a neat freak and the other is a slob. The combination leads to hilarious results. There will be two shows - a male version and a female version. The male version will be Dec. 16 at 6:30 p.m. and the female version will be Dec. 17 at 6:30 p.m. Both shows will be at the NCHS large auditorium. Tickets are $2 for students and staff of NCHS and $5 for the community. #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles #OddCouple #Drama

post_text: Infinity Early College HS student Tyler Mattingly invited U.S. Rep. Kevin Brady to his school to talk about the economy and the future of employment. Mattingly had been trying to get Congressman Brady to visit his school for the past three months and he learned just before the Thanksgiving Break that he would stop by and visit. Brady discussed the current U.S. economy and encouraged the students to be lifelong learners for the changing economy of the future. He also answered questions about topics such as the future of Social Security, entrepreneurship, and the rise of automation in the future economy. Thank you Congressman Brady for visiting Infinity ECHS and New Caney ISD. #NCISD #IEC_Knights #TCOB #KevinBrady

post_text: NCHS Cosmetology students visited Keefer Crossing MS College and Career Readiness and Career Investigations class. They put together learning stations that included braiding, barbering and makeup skills. Students learned new hands-on skills at each station and participated in fun team building activities. Secretary Rachell Bravo said, “Going to the middle school has inspired me to start teaching.” Dulce Mejia said that her favorite part was teaching the students how to braid. “I loved going back to my old middle school and teaching. I was inspired by this event to become an educator,” said Mejia. The students ended the class with a team building activity that had everyone excited about starting their high school career. #NCISD #NCHS_Eagles #KCMS_Eagles #Cosmetology

post_text: Congratulations to the Woodridge Forest Middle School 8th grade football A-team. They recently won the District Championship with an undefeated 8-0 record. They defeated Creekwood Middle School by a score of 38-7 in the championship game. The defense was the top-ranked defense in the district allowing only 21 points the entire season and recorded a total of six shutouts. The offense averaged 26 points a game which was good for second best in the district. #NCISD #WFMS_Spartans

post_text: The Spartan Marching Band has advanced to the UIL Texas State Marching Contest and will travel to San Antonio Sunday to perform Monday November 4 at 9:30 a.m. in the Alamodome. The marching band thus far this season has either won or placed at the top of all marching contests they have competed in this fall. They were 1st place champions at the Galena Park ISD contest, 2nd overall in the US Bands Conroe / Dekaney Contest, 1st in conference 5A at the Lonestar Preview Contest in Conroe, with straight first divisions at UIL Region 33 Marching Contest, and a 3rd place finish at UIL Area I, qualifying for the UIL State Marching contest for the second time in two years. Saturday's finish was the highest ever in the history of the band program, placing 3rd in Area I, and also being the only band in UIL Region 33 to advance to the state level. Congratulations Spartan Marching Band! #NCISD #PHS_Spartans

post_text: PHS Engineering had a great time competing in the BEST Robotics Competition recently and are advancing to Regionals for the 8th straight year. The team earned 2nd place overall out of 14 teams. BEST Robotics is six weeks long and consists of two different main areas; Engineering and Marketing. The student team is given a theme each year and must design a robot to solve a real-world problem based on the theme and create a company to sell their robot. The team had to design and build a robot to simulate a lineman restoring electrical power after a catastrophic event by reconnecting power lines, installing transformers, laying conduit, and removing dangerous debris. #NCISD #PHS_Spartans
